author: Hani95
body:
They went up significantly for WeBull (To 170% as far as I was told). Apparantly, the Ortex Rate is still high. Please also note that there were 400-450k Shares to borrow on IBKR, and only 45k (Last i checked) has been returned. That leaves 350-400k borrowed which is still the vast majority. 

My guess, is they are actually doing Due Diligence of their own and have realized we've been bandying around the IBKR numbers, so their trying to mask their movement a little. With that said, at the end of the day only 45-50k has been been returned to IBKR leaving a very significant amount left over. They haven't really begun to cover.

Finally, if you're going to sell your shares, and are cognizant of the gamma squeeze for the love of god sell deep ITM covered calls instead. Gets you out with guaranteed profit (and ekes you an extra percentage point or two), while simultaneously not hurting the upward momentum of the stock for Friday since the Market Makers will need to hedge before it ends above 9.

author: yukhateeee
body:
I need to do a deeper dive on the financials, but I believe that "betting" is going to be the next "gaming".  ie a new socially acceptable form of entertainment.  I know that gambling has always existed, but never to this level of convenience.  

The confluence of legalization and the convenience of a "always with us" smartphone app - is a new long term investment opportunity.  As with any "new" venture, there will be ups & downs - ie risk & reward.  

Obviously, I'm a bull, but cognizant of the risks AND I'm loss-averse - so I'll make long-term plays.  Timing of these trades will  be many months to years (LEAPs).  

* Modified synthetic longs to establish long term "long positions". 
* Bullish long diagonals to "accumulate house money for future bets".  
* Neutral long diagonals to hedge for the inevitable downturns.  

BTW:  Here's where I discussed "modified synthetic longs".  redditors were not impressed :-( I think, they favor shorter term trades. 

[https://www.reddit.com/r/options/comments/gy513z/share\_a\_longterm\_options\_strategy\_heres\_mine/](https://www.reddit.com/r/options/comments/gy513z/share_a_longterm_options_strategy_heres_mine/)

author: lattiboy
body:
Because everybody thinks their “rules of investing” are universal when everybody is just kind of winging this in the end. I’m still up a whole lot since Jan, but I’ve also lost over 20% in April.

Now, there’ll be a person on here who will say “I’m down .05% today” on a bad day and my blood will boil, but then I remember when I almost doubled my money in two weeks with some very well timed tech options. Always cognizant that I could lose 50% of my money and be back to square one with a few really bad weeks for my calls. 

Although, even as a risky trader, ARK often seems insane to me. Their PLTR and TESLA positions are quasi indefensible, but then again Cathie has beaten the shit out of pretty much everybody else over the last two years last time I checked. Even with the recent bloodletting

author: Sir_Lancelot_Papaya
body:
What im saying is people need to be more cognizant of the different obtainable customers for opportunities to “tour space” through virgin/Blue or spaceX. Orbital travel will require a lot of training (literally for the participant, on top of what virgin/blue travelers already have to get) to be comfortable with the 3-5G load sustained in flight. Things like this point to spce and blue being the primary adoption vessel for “tourism” for whatever that experience will become. 
A couple minute view above the VK line and weightlessness? Or a a couple day stay in a space station? One is further fetched then the other and theres a reason why SpaceX is staying private/sustaining off of satellite launches/iss trips. I know someone can’t wait to suck Elon off and say “but wait! Some billionaire already agreed to be the first tourist, spacex to the moon!” Thats not going to happen for a few years, let alone, the average billionaire. What a world.
